I now have a comprehensive understanding of the codebase. Let me summarize my findings and produce the detailed implementation plan.

---

## Detailed Implementation Plan: Custom Theme System for T3 Code

### Architecture Overview

The plan introduces a two-layer theme system:

1. **Data layer** (`packages/shared/src/themes.ts`): Pure theme definitions and lookup functions, shareable across the monorepo. No React, no DOM.
2. **Application layer** (`apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts`): Extended hook that combines the existing light/dark/system behavior with named theme selection, applying CSS custom properties to the document root.

---

### Step 1: Create `packages/shared/src/themes.ts`

**Purpose**: Define the `Theme` interface, three built-in themes, and pure lookup functions.

**Type definitions**:

```ts
export interface ThemeColors {
  background: string;
  foreground: string;
  card: string;
  cardForeground: string;
  popover: string;
  popoverForeground: string;
  primary: string;
  primaryForeground: string;
  secondary: string;
  secondaryForeground: string;
  muted: string;
  mutedForeground: string;
  accent: string;
  accentForeground: string;
  destructive: string;
  destructiveForeground: string;
  border: string;
  input: string;
  ring: string;
  info: string;
  infoForeground: string;
  success: string;
  successForeground: string;
  warning: string;
  warningForeground: string;
  // New region-specific colors
  sidebar: string;
  sidebarForeground: string;
  editor: string;
  editorForeground: string;
  terminal: string;
  terminalForeground: string;
  statusBar: string;
  statusBarForeground: string;
}

export interface ThemeDefinition {
  readonly id: string;
  readonly name: string;
  readonly appearance: "light" | "dark";
  readonly colors: ThemeColors;
  readonly fontFamily: string;
  readonly fontSize: number;
}
```

**Key design decisions in this type**:

- `appearance: "light" | "dark"` -- Every named theme declares whether it is visually light or dark. This drives the `.dark` class toggle on `<html>`, preserving Tailwind's `@variant dark` behavior. This is the crucial bridge between named themes and the existing system.
- The `colors` object maps **one-to-one** with CSS custom properties. The naming uses camelCase in TypeScript and kebab-case in CSS (`cardForeground` maps to `--card-foreground`).
- Region-specific colors (`sidebar`, `editor`, `terminal`, `statusBar`) are new CSS custom properties that do not exist today. They will be introduced in `index.css` with sensible defaults, so existing CSS continues to work even without the theme system applying inline styles.
- `fontFamily` and `fontSize` are stored as metadata but **not** applied as CSS custom properties on the root element in the initial implementation. They are available for future use by the editor and terminal components. This avoids disturbing the existing font stack in `body` and `pre, code`.

**Built-in themes**:

```ts
const T3_DARK: ThemeDefinition = {
  id: "t3-dark",
  name: "T3 Dark",
  appearance: "dark",
  colors: {
    // Values matching the current @variant dark block in index.css
    background: "color-mix(in srgb, #0a0a0a 95%, #ffffff)",
    foreground: "#f5f5f5",
    // ... all existing dark values
    sidebar: "color-mix(in srgb, #0a0a0a 93%, #ffffff)",
    sidebarForeground: "#f5f5f5",
    editor: "color-mix(in srgb, #0a0a0a 95%, #ffffff)",
    editorForeground: "#f5f5f5",
    terminal: "#0a0a0a",
    terminalForeground: "#e5e5e5",
    statusBar: "color-mix(in srgb, #0a0a0a 90%, #ffffff)",
    statusBarForeground: "#f5f5f5",
  },
  fontFamily: '"DM Sans", -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI", system-ui, sans-serif',
  fontSize: 14,
};

const T3_LIGHT: ThemeDefinition = {
  id: "t3-light",
  name: "T3 Light",
  appearance: "light",
  colors: {
    // Values matching the current :root block in index.css
    background: "#ffffff",
    foreground: "#262626",
    // ... all existing light values
    sidebar: "#fafafa",
    sidebarForeground: "#262626",
    editor: "#ffffff",
    editorForeground: "#262626",
    terminal: "#ffffff",
    terminalForeground: "#262626",
    statusBar: "#f5f5f5",
    statusBarForeground: "#262626",
  },
  fontFamily: '"DM Sans", -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI", system-ui, sans-serif',
  fontSize: 14,
};

const T3_MIDNIGHT: ThemeDefinition = {
  id: "t3-midnight",
  name: "T3 Midnight",
  appearance: "dark",
  colors: {
    // Deeper, more saturated dark theme with blue undertones
    background: "#0b0e14",
    foreground: "#c8ccd4",
    card: "#0d1117",
    cardForeground: "#c8ccd4",
    // ... distinct midnight palette
    primary: "oklch(0.65 0.25 264)",
    sidebar: "#080b10",
    sidebarForeground: "#8b92a0",
    editor: "#0b0e14",
    editorForeground: "#c8ccd4",
    terminal: "#070a0f",
    terminalForeground: "#a0a8b8",
    statusBar: "#0d1017",
    statusBarForeground: "#8b92a0",
  },
  fontFamily: '"DM Sans", -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI", system-ui, sans-serif',
  fontSize: 14,
};
```

**Exported functions** (following the `model.ts` pure-function pattern):

```ts
const THEMES: ReadonlyArray<ThemeDefinition> = [T3_DARK, T3_LIGHT, T3_MIDNIGHT];
const THEME_MAP = new Map<string, ThemeDefinition>(THEMES.map((t) => [t.id, t]));

export function listThemes(): ReadonlyArray<ThemeDefinition> {
  return THEMES;
}

export function getTheme(id: string): ThemeDefinition | undefined {
  return THEME_MAP.get(id);
}

export function getDefaultThemeId(): string {
  return "t3-dark";
}
```

**Note**: This module must have zero dependencies on `@t3tools/contracts` or `effect`. It is pure TypeScript with no imports, keeping the module lightweight and free of the Effect runtime.

---

### Step 2: Add Subpath Export to `packages/shared/package.json`

Add the following entry to the `"exports"` field:

```json
"./themes": {
  "types": "./src/themes.ts",
  "import": "./src/themes.ts"
}
```

This follows the exact pattern used by `./model`, `./git`, `./logging`, `./shell`, and `./Net`.

---

### Step 3: Add New CSS Custom Properties to `apps/web/src/index.css`

**Rationale**: The sidebar component (`sidebar.tsx`) already references `bg-sidebar`, `text-sidebar-foreground`, `border-sidebar-border`, and `bg-sidebar-accent`. These require CSS variables `--sidebar`, `--sidebar-foreground`, etc. Currently these are undefined (which means Tailwind falls back to transparent or the computed inherits). The new theme system will set them via inline styles, but we also need CSS-level defaults for when no theme has been applied yet (the initial page load before JS runs, or if JS fails).

Add to the `:root` block in `index.css`:

```css
/* Region-specific surfaces */
--sidebar: var(--card);
--sidebar-foreground: var(--card-foreground);
--sidebar-border: var(--border);
--sidebar-accent: var(--accent);
--sidebar-accent-foreground: var(--accent-foreground);
--sidebar-ring: var(--ring);
--editor: var(--background);
--editor-foreground: var(--foreground);
--terminal: var(--background);
--terminal-foreground: var(--foreground);
--status-bar: var(--muted);
--status-bar-foreground: var(--muted-foreground);
```

Also add these within the `@variant dark { ... }` block (they can just reference the dark-mode equivalents of the same generic vars, since `--card`, `--background`, etc. are redefined inside `@variant dark`):

```css
--sidebar: var(--card);
--sidebar-foreground: var(--card-foreground);
--sidebar-border: var(--border);
--sidebar-accent: var(--accent);
--sidebar-accent-foreground: var(--accent-foreground);
--sidebar-ring: var(--ring);
--editor: var(--background);
--editor-foreground: var(--foreground);
--terminal: var(--background);
--terminal-foreground: var(--foreground);
--status-bar: var(--muted);
--status-bar-foreground: var(--muted-foreground);
```

Register these in the `@theme inline` block so Tailwind can generate utility classes:

```css
--color-sidebar: var(--sidebar);
--color-sidebar-foreground: var(--sidebar-foreground);
--color-sidebar-border: var(--sidebar-border);
--color-sidebar-accent: var(--sidebar-accent);
--color-sidebar-accent-foreground: var(--sidebar-accent-foreground);
--color-sidebar-ring: var(--sidebar-ring);
--color-editor: var(--editor);
--color-editor-foreground: var(--editor-foreground);
--color-terminal: var(--terminal);
--color-terminal-foreground: var(--terminal-foreground);
--color-status-bar: var(--status-bar);
--color-status-bar-foreground: var(--status-bar-foreground);
```

This means `bg-sidebar`, `text-sidebar-foreground`, `bg-editor`, `text-terminal-foreground`, etc. all become valid Tailwind utilities. The sidebar component already uses some of these, and they will now resolve correctly.

---

### Step 4: Extend the `useTheme` Hook (`apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts`)

This is the most delicate change. The existing hook manages three concerns:
1. Storing light/dark/system preference in localStorage
2. Toggling the `.dark` CSS class
3. Suppressing CSS transitions during switches

The new hook needs to add:
4. Storing a named theme ID in localStorage
5. Applying that theme's CSS custom properties as inline styles on `<html>`
6. Exposing `availableThemes` and `activeTheme` to consumers

**Migration strategy for localStorage**:

- **New key**: `"t3code:named-theme"` stores the theme ID string (e.g., `"t3-dark"`, `"t3-light"`, `"t3-midnight"`).
- **Old key**: `"t3code:theme"` continues to work. On first load, if `"t3code:named-theme"` is absent but `"t3code:theme"` is present, migrate: `"dark"` maps to `"t3-dark"`, `"light"` maps to `"t3-light"`, `"system"` maps to no named theme override (use appearance-based resolution).
- **System preference**: Retained as a concept. When the user selects "System" mode, the hook picks the theme whose `appearance` matches the OS preference. The user can also explicitly select a named theme, which implicitly sets the mode to that theme's appearance.

**New snapshot type**:

```ts
type ThemeMode = "light" | "dark" | "system";
type ThemeSnapshot = {
  mode: ThemeMode;               // preserved from old system
  namedThemeId: string | null;   // null means "auto" (use mode to pick)
  systemDark: boolean;
};
```

**Resolution logic**:

```ts
function resolveActiveTheme(snapshot: ThemeSnapshot): ThemeDefinition {
  // If user has explicitly selected a named theme, use it
  if (snapshot.namedThemeId) {
    const theme = getTheme(snapshot.namedThemeId);
    if (theme) return theme;
  }
  // Otherwise, derive from mode
  const isDark = snapshot.mode === "dark" || 
    (snapshot.mode === "system" && snapshot.systemDark);
  return isDark ? getTheme("t3-dark")! : getTheme("t3-light")!;
}
```

**CSS application function**:

```ts
function applyThemeColors(theme: ThemeDefinition): void {
  const style = document.documentElement.style;
  // Apply each color as a CSS custom property
  // camelCase -> kebab-case conversion
  for (const [key, value] of Object.entries(theme.colors)) {
    const cssVar = `--${camelToKebab(key)}`;
    style.setProperty(cssVar, value);
  }
}

function camelToKebab(str: string): string {
  return str.replace(/[A-Z]/g, (m) => `-${m.toLowerCase()}`);
}
```

The existing `applyTheme()` function is modified to also call `applyThemeColors()`:

```ts
function applyTheme(theme: ThemeDefinition, suppressTransitions = false) {
  if (suppressTransitions) {
    document.documentElement.classList.add("no-transitions");
  }

  // Toggle .dark based on theme appearance
  document.documentElement.classList.toggle("dark", theme.appearance === "dark");

  // Apply CSS custom properties
  applyThemeColors(theme);

  if (suppressTransitions) {
    document.documentElement.offsetHeight; // force reflow
    requestAnimationFrame(() => {
      document.documentElement.classList.remove("no-transitions");
    });
  }
}
```

**Updated hook return type**:

```ts
export function useTheme() {
  // ... useSyncExternalStore as before, but with new snapshot shape

  return {
    // Backwards-compatible fields
    theme: snapshot.mode,                           // "light" | "dark" | "system"
    setTheme: setMode,                              // (mode: ThemeMode) => void
    resolvedTheme: activeTheme.appearance,           // "light" | "dark"

    // New fields
    activeTheme,                                     // ThemeDefinition
    namedThemeId: snapshot.namedThemeId,             // string | null
    setNamedTheme,                                   // (id: string) => void
    availableThemes: listThemes(),                   // ReadonlyArray<ThemeDefinition>
  } as const;
}
```

**Backwards compatibility**: The `theme`, `setTheme`, and `resolvedTheme` fields preserve their existing semantics. All five existing consumers (settings page, ChatMarkdown, ChatView, DiffPanel, DiffWorkerPoolProvider) use only `resolvedTheme` (a `"light" | "dark"` string) and `setTheme`. They continue to work unchanged.

**Module-load initialization**: The existing `applyTheme(getStored())` call at module level is replaced with:

```ts
const initialTheme = resolveActiveTheme(getSnapshot());
applyTheme(initialTheme);
```

This runs synchronously on import, preventing any flash, exactly as before.

---

### Step 5: Create ThemeSelector Component (`apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx`)

A new component that displays theme options with visual preview swatches.

**Structure**:

```tsx
import { useTheme } from "~/hooks/useTheme";
import type { ThemeDefinition } from "@t3tools/shared/themes";

function ThemeSwatch({ theme, selected, onClick }: {
  theme: ThemeDefinition;
  selected: boolean;
  onClick: () => void;
}) {
  return (
    <button
      type="button"
      role="radio"
      aria-checked={selected}
      className={cn(
        "flex w-full items-start gap-3 rounded-lg border px-3 py-2 text-left transition-colors",
        selected
          ? "border-primary/60 bg-primary/8 text-foreground"
          : "border-border bg-background text-muted-foreground hover:bg-accent"
      )}
      onClick={onClick}
    >
      {/* Color swatch preview */}
      <div className="flex shrink-0 gap-0.5 rounded-md overflow-hidden border border-border">
        <div className="h-8 w-4" style={{ background: theme.colors.sidebar }} />
        <div className="h-8 w-6" style={{ background: theme.colors.editor }} />
        <div className="h-8 w-4" style={{ background: theme.colors.terminal }} />
      </div>
      <span className="flex flex-col">
        <span className="text-sm font-medium">{theme.name}</span>
        <span className="text-xs capitalize">{theme.appearance} theme</span>
      </span>
      {selected ? (
        <span className="ml-auto rounded bg-primary/14 px-1.5 py-0.5 text-[10px] font-medium uppercase tracking-wide text-primary">
          Active
        </span>
      ) : null}
    </button>
  );
}

export function ThemeSelector() {
  const { activeTheme, setNamedTheme, availableThemes } = useTheme();

  return (
    <div className="space-y-2" role="radiogroup" aria-label="Theme">
      {availableThemes.map((theme) => (
        <ThemeSwatch
          key={theme.id}
          theme={theme}
          selected={activeTheme.id === theme.id}
          onClick={() => setNamedTheme(theme.id)}
        />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

This follows the existing pattern in the settings page (radiogroup of styled buttons with selected indicator), but adds color swatch previews.

---

### Step 6: Update Settings Page (`apps/web/src/routes/_chat.settings.tsx`)

The Appearance section currently renders three radio buttons for "System", "Light", "Dark". This needs to change to show the named themes, plus a "System" toggle for auto-detection.

**Changes**:

1. Remove the inline `THEME_OPTIONS` array (lines 25-41).
2. Import `ThemeSelector` from `~/components/ThemeSelector`.
3. Replace the radiogroup rendering with `<ThemeSelector />`.
4. Add a separate "Auto-detect" toggle (using the existing `Switch` component) that toggles between named-theme mode and system mode. When "Auto-detect" is on, the system picks the theme based on OS preference (cycling between `t3-light` and `t3-dark`). When off, the user's explicit named theme choice is used.
5. The "Active theme" indicator at the bottom of the section updates to show the theme name instead of just "light"/"dark".

The `useTheme()` destructuring changes from:
```ts
const { theme, setTheme, resolvedTheme } = useTheme();
```
to:
```ts
const { theme, setTheme, resolvedTheme, activeTheme, setNamedTheme, availableThemes } = useTheme();
```

The settings section becomes:

```tsx
<section className="rounded-2xl border border-border bg-card p-5">
  <div className="mb-4">
    <h2 className="text-sm font-medium text-foreground">Appearance</h2>
    <p className="mt-1 text-xs text-muted-foreground">
      Choose a theme for T3 Code.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div className="mb-4 flex items-center justify-between rounded-lg border border-border bg-background px-3 py-2">
    <div>
      <p className="text-sm font-medium text-foreground">Match system appearance</p>
      <p className="text-xs text-muted-foreground">
        Automatically switch between light and dark themes.
      </p>
    </div>
    <Switch
      checked={theme === "system"}
      onCheckedChange={(checked) => {
        if (checked) {
          setTheme("system");
        } else {
          setNamedTheme(activeTheme.id);
        }
      }}
    />
  </div>

  <ThemeSelector />

  <p className="mt-4 text-xs text-muted-foreground">
    Active theme: <span className="font-medium text-foreground">{activeTheme.name}</span>
  </p>
</section>
```

---

### Step 7: No Provider/Context Needed

A deliberate architectural choice: this design does **not** introduce a React Context provider. The existing `useTheme` hook uses `useSyncExternalStore` with module-level state, which is already a global singleton. Adding a context would:
- Require wrapping the app in a new provider in `__root.tsx`
- Add unnecessary re-render boundaries
- Conflict with the existing module-load initialization pattern

The `useSyncExternalStore` approach is the right pattern here and is already proven in both `useTheme.ts` and `appSettings.ts`.

---

### Step 8: Write Tests for `packages/shared/src/themes.ts`

Create `packages/shared/src/themes.test.ts` following the existing `model.test.ts` pattern:

```ts
import { describe, expect, it } from "vitest";
import { getTheme, listThemes, getDefaultThemeId } from "./themes";

describe("listThemes", () => {
  it("returns at least 3 built-in themes", () => {
    expect(listThemes().length).toBeGreaterThanOrEqual(3);
  });

  it("includes t3-dark, t3-light, and t3-midnight", () => {
    const ids = listThemes().map((t) => t.id);
    expect(ids).toContain("t3-dark");
    expect(ids).toContain("t3-light");
    expect(ids).toContain("t3-midnight");
  });
});

describe("getTheme", () => {
  it("returns a theme by id", () => {
    const theme = getTheme("t3-dark");
    expect(theme).toBeDefined();
    expect(theme!.name).toBe("T3 Dark");
