# Custom Theme System — Implementation Plan

## Context

T3 Code currently has a basic light/dark/system appearance toggle (`apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts`) that flips a `.dark` CSS class on `<html>` and lets Tailwind's `@variant dark` handle color changes. The user wants a richer **named theme** system with structured theme definitions, multiple built-in palettes, preview swatches, and CSS custom property application — while preserving full backwards compatibility with the existing dark-mode machinery.

The sidebar component (`ui/sidebar.tsx`) already references Tailwind classes like `bg-sidebar`, `text-sidebar-foreground`, `border-sidebar-border` — but the underlying CSS variables are **not yet defined** in `index.css`, so these need to be added.

---

## Files to Create

| # | File | Purpose |
|---|------|---------|
| 1 | `packages/shared/src/themes.ts` | Theme types, 3 built-in themes, `getTheme()` / `listThemes()` |
| 2 | `packages/shared/src/themes.test.ts` | Unit tests for the data layer |
| 3 | `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx` | Theme picker with color swatches |

## Files to Modify

| # | File | Change |
|---|------|--------|
| 4 | `packages/shared/package.json` | Add `"./themes"` subpath export |
| 5 | `apps/web/src/index.css` | Add sidebar/editor/terminal/statusBar CSS variables + register in `@theme inline` |
| 6 | `apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts` | Extend with named-theme support, CSS property application |
| 7 | `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.settings.tsx` | Replace appearance section with `ThemeSelector` + system-mode toggle |

---

## Step 1 — `packages/shared/src/themes.ts` (new file)

Define types and data. Pure TypeScript, **zero dependencies** (no Effect, no contracts).

### Types

```ts
export interface ThemeColors {
  background: string;
  foreground: string;
  card: string;
  cardForeground: string;
  popover: string;
  popoverForeground: string;
  primary: string;
  primaryForeground: string;
  secondary: string;
  secondaryForeground: string;
  muted: string;
  mutedForeground: string;
  accent: string;
  accentForeground: string;
  destructive: string;
  destructiveForeground: string;
  border: string;
  input: string;
  ring: string;
  info: string;
  infoForeground: string;
  success: string;
  successForeground: string;
  warning: string;
  warningForeground: string;
  sidebar: string;
  sidebarForeground: string;
  editor: string;
  editorForeground: string;
  terminal: string;
  terminalForeground: string;
  statusBar: string;
  statusBarForeground: string;
}

export interface ThemeDefinition {
  readonly id: string;
  readonly name: string;
  readonly appearance: "light" | "dark";  // drives .dark class toggle
  readonly colors: ThemeColors;
  readonly fontFamily: string;
  readonly fontSize: number;
}
```

The `appearance` field is the bridge between named themes and the existing `.dark` class system.

### Built-in Themes

- **`t3-dark`** — Default. Colors match the current `@variant dark` block in `index.css` (neutral-950 backgrounds, oklch(0.588 0.217 264) primary, neutral-100 foreground).
- **`t3-light`** — Colors match the current `:root` block (white background, neutral-800 foreground, oklch(0.488 0.217 264) primary).
- **`t3-midnight`** — Deeper dark theme with blue undertones (`#0b0e14` background, `#c8ccd4` foreground, brighter blue-violet primary).

All three define the complete `ThemeColors` set, including the new region-specific keys (`sidebar`, `editor`, `terminal`, `statusBar`).

### Exports

```ts
export function listThemes(): ReadonlyArray<ThemeDefinition>
export function getTheme(id: string): ThemeDefinition | undefined
export function getDefaultThemeId(): string   // returns "t3-dark"
```

Follows the pure-function pattern from `packages/shared/src/model.ts`.

---

## Step 2 — `packages/shared/package.json`

Add one entry to `"exports"`:

```json
"./themes": {
  "types": "./src/themes.ts",
  "import": "./src/themes.ts"
}
```

Follows the exact pattern of `./model`, `./git`, etc.

---

## Step 3 — `apps/web/src/index.css`

The sidebar component already uses Tailwind classes `bg-sidebar`, `text-sidebar-foreground`, `border-sidebar-border`, `bg-sidebar-accent`, `text-sidebar-accent-foreground`, `ring-sidebar-ring` — but the CSS variables backing them are missing.

### Add to `:root` block (after existing vars, before `@variant dark`):

```css
--sidebar: var(--card);
--sidebar-foreground: var(--card-foreground);
--sidebar-border: var(--border);
--sidebar-accent: var(--accent);
--sidebar-accent-foreground: var(--accent-foreground);
--sidebar-ring: var(--ring);
--editor: var(--background);
--editor-foreground: var(--foreground);
--terminal: var(--background);
--terminal-foreground: var(--foreground);
--status-bar: var(--muted);
--status-bar-foreground: var(--muted-foreground);
```

### Add same vars inside `@variant dark { ... }` block

(They reference the same generic vars, which are re-defined for dark mode.)

### Register in `@theme inline` block

```css
--color-sidebar: var(--sidebar);
--color-sidebar-foreground: var(--sidebar-foreground);
--color-editor: var(--editor);
--color-editor-foreground: var(--editor-foreground);
--color-terminal: var(--terminal);
--color-terminal-foreground: var(--terminal-foreground);
--color-status-bar: var(--status-bar);
--color-status-bar-foreground: var(--status-bar-foreground);
```

Note: `--color-sidebar-border`, `--color-sidebar-accent`, `--color-sidebar-accent-foreground`, `--color-sidebar-ring` may already be registered by the sidebar component's Tailwind usage — check and add only if missing.

---

## Step 4 — `apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts`

This is the core change. Extend the existing `useSyncExternalStore`-based hook.

### New localStorage key

- `"t3code:named-theme"` — stores the theme ID string (e.g. `"t3-dark"`)
- Existing `"t3code:theme"` key is kept for the light/dark/system mode

### Migration on first load

If `"t3code:named-theme"` is absent but `"t3code:theme"` exists:
- `"dark"` → set named theme to `"t3-dark"`
- `"light"` → set named theme to `"t3-light"`
- `"system"` → leave named theme `null` (auto-resolve from OS preference)

### New snapshot shape

```ts
type ThemeSnapshot = {
  mode: "light" | "dark" | "system";
  namedThemeId: string | null;
  systemDark: boolean;
};
```

### Resolution logic

```ts
function resolveActiveTheme(snapshot: ThemeSnapshot): ThemeDefinition {
  if (snapshot.namedThemeId) {
    const theme = getTheme(snapshot.namedThemeId);
    if (theme) return theme;
  }
  const isDark = snapshot.mode === "dark" ||
    (snapshot.mode === "system" && snapshot.systemDark);
  return isDark ? getTheme("t3-dark")! : getTheme("t3-light")!;
}
```

### CSS application

```ts
function applyThemeColors(theme: ThemeDefinition): void {
  const style = document.documentElement.style;
  for (const [key, value] of Object.entries(theme.colors)) {
    style.setProperty(`--${camelToKebab(key)}`, value);
  }
}

function camelToKebab(str: string): string {
  return str.replace(/[A-Z]/g, (m) => `-${m.toLowerCase()}`);
}
```

The existing `applyTheme()` function is updated to accept a `ThemeDefinition`, toggle `.dark` based on `theme.appearance`, and call `applyThemeColors()`.

### Updated hook return (backwards-compatible)

```ts
return {
  // Existing fields (unchanged signatures)
  theme: snapshot.mode,                    // "light" | "dark" | "system"
  setTheme: setMode,                       // (mode) => void
  resolvedTheme: activeTheme.appearance,   // "light" | "dark"

  // New fields
  activeTheme,                             // ThemeDefinition
  namedThemeId: snapshot.namedThemeId,     // string | null
  setNamedTheme,                           // (id: string) => void
  availableThemes: listThemes(),           // ReadonlyArray<ThemeDefinition>
} as const;
```

**Backwards compatibility**: All 5 existing consumers (`_chat.settings.tsx`, `ChatMarkdown.tsx`, `ChatView.tsx`, `DiffPanel.tsx`, `DiffWorkerPoolProvider.tsx`) destructure only `{ theme, setTheme, resolvedTheme }`. Since those fields keep the same types and semantics, no consumer needs changes (except the settings page, which we update intentionally).

### Module-load initialization

Replace `applyTheme(getStored())` with:

```ts
const initialTheme = resolveActiveTheme(getSnapshot());
applyThemeDom(initialTheme);
```

This runs synchronously on import, preventing flash — same behavior as today.

### Cross-tab sync

Extend the existing `storage` event handler to also listen for changes to `"t3code:named-theme"`.

---

## Step 5 — `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx` (new file)

A radiogroup of theme option buttons, each with a color swatch preview.

### Structure

```tsx
export function ThemeSelector() {
  const { activeTheme, setNamedTheme, availableThemes } = useTheme();

  return (
    <div className="space-y-2" role="radiogroup" aria-label="Theme">
      {availableThemes.map((t) => (
        <ThemeSwatch key={t.id} theme={t} selected={activeTheme.id === t.id}
          onClick={() => setNamedTheme(t.id)} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

Each `ThemeSwatch` renders:
- A mini color preview (3 vertical bars showing sidebar / editor / terminal colors via inline `style`)
- Theme name and appearance label
- "Active" badge when selected

Follows the existing settings-page radio button pattern (`border-primary/60 bg-primary/8` when selected).

Uses: `cn()` from `~/lib/utils`, `useTheme` from `~/hooks/useTheme`, `ThemeDefinition` type from `@t3tools/shared/themes`.

---

## Step 6 — `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.settings.tsx`

### Changes to Appearance section (lines 202–243)

1. Remove the inline `THEME_OPTIONS` constant (lines 25-41).
2. Import `ThemeSelector` from `~/components/ThemeSelector`.
3. Destructure new fields: `const { theme, setTheme, resolvedTheme, activeTheme, setNamedTheme } = useTheme();`
4. Replace the radiogroup with `<ThemeSelector />`.
5. Add a "Match system appearance" `Switch` toggle above the theme list:
   - When ON → `setTheme("system")` (auto-resolve from OS)
   - When OFF → `setNamedTheme(activeTheme.id)` (lock to current theme)
6. Update the "Active theme" label to show `activeTheme.name` instead of just `resolvedTheme`.

---

## Step 7 — `packages/shared/src/themes.test.ts` (new file)

Tests using vitest (run with `bun run test` from `packages/shared`):

